[1mRecipe structure:[22m[0m[0m
- **The Problem.** Opens with a payment-integrity analyst's Thursday queue of 142K claims across 18K providers; walks through five concrete anomaly flavors (E&M drift, uniform PT code sequences, unit rounding, modifier 59 abuse, lab mix shifts).[0m[0m
- **The Technology.** Teaches the point/contextual/collective anomaly taxonomy, the three comparison axes (self / peer / case-mix-adjusted), feature families, statistical methods (z-scores, CUSUM, Isolation Forest, matrix factorization, supervised classifiers), the peer-group definition problem, the labeling pitfalls, and the fairness/harassment concerns. All vendor-agnostic.[0m[0m
- **General Architecture Pattern.** ASCII diagram of the four-stage continuous-profiling pipeline plus the feedback loop.[0m[0m
- **AWS Implementation.** Why These Services, Mermaid architecture diagram, Prerequisites table, Ingredients table, 5-step pseudocode walkthrough (rollup, peer groups, scoring, case assembly, outcome capture + retraining), sample case-record JSON (upcoding case and specialty-atypical case), benchmark tables, "where it struggles" list.[0m[0m
- **Why This Isn't Production-Ready.** Provider entity resolution, peer-group tuning, case deduplication, analyst tooling, legal review, communication protocols, explainability, fairness monitoring, retention, false-positive handling, drift monitoring, and cost-per-case tracking.[0m[0m
- **The Honest Take.** First-person CC-style reflections.[0m[0m
- **Variations, Related Recipes, Additional Resources, Implementation Time, Tags, Navigation.** Full sections per RECIPE-GUIDE.md.[0m[0m
